Human infection with B virus following a needlestick injury.
 A 26-year-old veterinary technician who became infected with B virus at the site of a needlestick injury is described.
 After the patient was treated with intravenous acyclovir, all cultures became negative for B virus and have remained so during treatment with oral acyclovir.
 The literature on infections due to B virus in humans is reviewed, and a detailed discussion of the various aspects of this simian herpesvirus is presented.
